05316nam a22009735i 9780520340909DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20202023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203409097 a10.1525/97805203409092doi  a(DE-B1597)543558  a(OCoLC)1153460877  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE169.12b.H49 1997eb 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a973.92211 aHenriksen, Margot A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDr. Strangelove's America :bSociety and Culture in the Atomic Age /cMargot A. Henriksen.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (469 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tPART 1. Knowing Sin -- tONE. Top of the world -- ttwo. Vertigo -- tPart 2. Psycho -- tthree. Duck and Cover -- tfour. The Snake Pit -- tfive. Wild Ones -- tpart 3. Is God Dead? -- tsix. Time enough at last? -- tseven. Laughter and a new myth of life -- teight. Judgment day -- tnine. Godless violence and transcendent hope -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDid America really learn to "stop worrying and love the bomb," as the title of Stanley Kubrick's 1964 film, Dr. Strangelove, would have us believe? Does that darkly satirical comedy have anything in common with Martin Luther King Jr.'s impassioned "I Have a Dream" speech or with Elvis Presley's throbbing "I'm All Shook Up"? In Margot Henriksen's vivid depiction of the decades after World War II, all three are expressions of a cultural revolution directly related to the atomic bomb. Although many scientists and other Americans protested the pursuit of nuclear superiority after World War II ended, they were drowned out by Cold War rhetoric that encouraged a "culture of consensus." Nonetheless, Henriksen says, a "culture of dissent" arose, and she traces this rebellion through all forms of popular culture.At first, artists expressed their anger, anxiety, and despair in familiar terms that addressed nuclear reality only indirectly. But Henriksen focuses primarily on new modes of expression that emerged, discussing the disturbing themes of film noir (with extended attention to Alfred Hitchcock) and science fiction films, Beat poetry, rock 'n' roll, and Pop Art. Black humor became a primary weapon in the cultural revolution while literature, movies, and music gave free rein to every possible expression of the generation gap. Cultural upheavals from "flower power" to the civil rights movement accentuated the failure of old values.Filled with fascinating examples of cultural responses to the Atomic Age, Henriksen's book is a must-read for anyone interested in the United States at mid-twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAtomic bombxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aAtomic bombxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aatom bomb.  aatomic age.  aatomic bomb.  abeat poetry.  ablack humor.  acivil rights movement.  acold war.  acultural revolution.  aculture of consensus.  adark humor.  adissent.  adr strangelove.  aelvis.  afilm noir.  aflower power.  ahistory.  ahitchcock.  ai have a dream.  amartin luther king jr.  amass media.  amusic.  anonfiction.  anuclear bomb.  anuclear power.  anuclear war.  apop art.  apopular culture.  arebellion.  arock and roll.  ascience fiction.  asocial change.  astanley kubrick.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 c